chunks.html_content:
Your will lets you decide what happens to your money, property and possessions after your death.

If you make a will you can also make sure you do not pay more Inheritance Tax than you need to.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
Your will lets you decide what happens to your money, property and possessions after your death.
If you make a will you can also make sure you do not pay more Inheritance Tax than you need to.

chunks.html_content: There are different rules for Scotland and different rules for Northern Ireland.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
There are different rules for Scotland and different rules for Northern Ireland.

chunks.html_content:
You can write your will yourself, but you should get advice if your will is not straightforward.

You need to get your will formally witnessed and signed to make it legally valid.

If you want to update your will, you need to make an official alteration (called a codicil) or make a new will.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
You can write your will yourself, but you should get advice if your will is not straightforward.
You need to get your will formally witnessed and signed to make it legally valid.
If you want to update your will, you need to make an official alteration (called a codicil) or make a new will.

chunks.html_content: If you die without a will, the law decides who gets what.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
If you die without a will, the law decides who gets what.

chunks.html_content:
Your will should set out:

  • who you want to benefit from your will
  • who should look after any children under 18
  • who is going to sort out your estate and carry out your wishes after your death (your executor)
  • what happens if the people you want to benefit die before you

You can also include a charity in your will.

You can get advice from a professional if your will is not straightforward, for example:

  • you share a property with someone who is not your husband, wife or civil partner
  • you want to leave money or property to a dependant who cannot care for themselves
  • you have several family members who may make a claim on your will, such as a second spouse or children from another marriage
  • your permanent home is outside the UK
  • you have property overseas
  • you have a business

chunks.html_content:
You can keep your will at your home or store it with:

  • your solicitor
  • your bank
  • a company that offers the storage of wills - you can search online
  • the national probate registry in Newcastle

Read full guidance on storing your will with the Probate Service.

You should tell your executor (the person youve chosen to carry out your will), a close friend or relative where your will is.

chunks.html_content:
For your will to be legally valid, you must:

  • be 18 or over
  • make it voluntarily
  • be of sound mind
  • make it in writing
  • sign it in the presence of 2 witnesses who are both over 18
  • have it signed by your 2 witnesses, in your presence

You and your witnesses must sign the same document.

When you sign your will, both of your witnesses must have a clear view of you and the act of signing.

You can ask someone to sign on your behalf if youre unable to do it.

When your witnesses sign your will, you must have a clear view of them and the act of signing. Your witnesses do not need to sign it at the same time as each other.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
Signing and witnessing your will
For your will to be legally valid, you must:

  be 18 or over
  make it voluntarily
  be of sound mind
  make it in writing
  sign it in the presence of 2 witnesses who are both over 18
  have it signed by your 2 witnesses, in your presence

You and your witnesses must sign the same document.
When you sign your will, both of your witnesses must have a clear view of you and the act of signing.
You can ask someone to sign on your behalf if youre unable to do it.
When your witnesses sign your will, you must have a clear view of them and the act of signing. Your witnesses do not need to sign it at the same time as each other.

chunks.html_content: You cannot leave your witnesses (or their married partners) anything in your will.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
Signing and witnessing your will
You cannot leave your witnesses (or their married partners) anything in your will.

chunks.html_content:
If you make any changes to your will you must follow the same signing and witnessing process.

If you cannot meet with your witnesses in person, you can watch each other sign your will remotely (for example by video conferencing).

You can only sign remotely in England or Wales.

Making a will
Signing and witnessing your will
Signing your will remotely
If you make any changes to your will you must follow the same signing and witnessing process.
If you cannot meet with your witnesses in person, you can watch each other sign your will remotely (for example by video conferencing).
You can only sign remotely in England or Wales.

chunks.html_content:
You should review your will every 5 years and after any major change in your life, for example:

  • getting separated or divorced
  • getting married (this cancels any will you made before)
  • having a child
  • moving house
  • if the executor named in the will dies

You cannot amend your will after its been signed and witnessed. The only way you can change a will is by making an official alteration called a codicil.

You must sign a codicil and get it witnessed in the same way as witnessing a will.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
Making changes to your will
You should review your will every 5 years and after any major change in your life, for example:

  getting separated or divorced
  getting married (this cancels any will you made before)
  having a child
  moving house
  if the executor named in the will dies

You cannot amend your will after its been signed and witnessed. The only way you can change a will is by making an official alteration called a codicil.
You must sign a codicil and get it witnessed in the same way as witnessing a will.

chunks.html_content: Theres no limit on how many codicils you can add to a will.
chunks.plain_content:
Making a will
Making changes to your will
Theres no limit on how many codicils you can add to a will.

chunks.html_content:
For major changes you should make a new will.

Your new will should explain that it revokes (officially cancels) all previous wills and codicils. You should destroy your old will by burning it or tearing it up.
